        "other_parliamentary_business": [
            {
                "body": "On 26 March, MPs debated transport accessibility for disabled people.\nThis was a Backbench Business debate led by Ruth Cadbury MP. Transport Minister Keir Mather MP responded on behalf of the Government.\nRead the transcript (https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2026-03-26/debates/6F78AF79-C039-474A-8ED5-DAEBC68F847B/TransportAccessibilityForDisabledPeople)\nWatch it in full (https://parliamentlive.tv/event/index/c8f7eeae-9e39-4c90-8efa-f3e1eecaccfd?in=14:02:11)\nRead the research briefing (https://commonslibrary.parliament.uk/research-briefings/cdp-2026-0048/)\nExplainer\nBackbench Business debates give MPs an opportunity to debate a topic of their choice, and receive a response from the Government.\nThey are a way to:\nraise awareness of an issue\nseek to influence government policy\nput the views of backbench MPs, political parties, and the Government on record.\nThey do not generally involve a vote on a particular action or decision.\nSee our visual explainer (https://ukparliament.shorthandstories.com/cet-backbench-business-debates/index.html) on how these debates work.\nYour UK Parliament newsletter\nSign up (https://parliament.us14.list-manage.com/subscribe?u=098af33234df9814f59fb205f&id=6e29cb1262) to a regular newsletter on the work of Parliament and how to get involved.\n",
